Advertising ROI Case Study

Ingram Micro Interview, 2018-03-08

Michael Johnson, mdjhnsn@tamu.edu

Overview

This notebook examines data related to advertising effectiveness

  • The client is a media buying agency that brokers television advertising slots for content producers.
  • The VP of Marketing has asked us to help evaluate which media slots have the highest ROI.
  • ROI = customer purchases that can be attributed to advertisements aired at specific times.

Import

Read in the Excel file containing the client’s data

  • File contains details on individual commercials that aired on TV beginning in 2014
  • Target is the attributed performance (“Response”) for each commercial, subject to cost constraint (“CPM”)
df <- read_excel("Response Database.xlsx", sheet = "Data", range = "A1:Q84802")
dim(df)
[1] 84801    17
Variable Description
Response The number of website visits attributed to the airing the commercial
Date Date the commercial actually aired
Time Time the commercial actually aired
Network Television channel in which the commercial was shown
Daypart Defines the part of the day and week in which the commercial ran across all networks and media types
Rate The amount of money paid for the commercial to air
Imps (000) The number of individuals estimated to have watched the commercial
CPM Rate divided by impressions = CPM (cost per thousand views)
Property Description of the placement of the commercial; will often include a program name
Start Indicates the earliest time of day in which the commercial may show
End Indicates the latest time of day in which the commercial may show
Length The length of the commercial which aired in seconds
Buy Type Represents the different methods in which the property was purchased.
C/B/S Indicates if the network that aired the commercial was cable, broadcast, or syndication
Program May resemble “Property” from above
Week of Starting Monday, the week in which the commercial aired
Creative Title The name of the commercial that aired - some brands have different creatives on air at once.

Transform

Create custom features, transform/normalize variables

  • Extract individual time/date elements
  • Lump together
df <- df %>% 
  mutate(
    Year = lubridate::year(Date),
    Month = month.abb[lubridate::month(Date)],
    Day = lubridate::day(Date),
    DayofWk = weekdays(Date),
    Hour = lubridate::hour(Time),
    Minute = lubridate::minute(Time),
    `Buy Type` = as.factor(`Buy Type`),
    Length = as.factor(Length),
    Rating = recode(
      cut(Response, breaks = c(0,15,30,60,Inf)),
      `(0,15]` = "Very Poor" , `(15,30]` = "Poor", `(30,60]` = "Good", `(60,Inf]` = "Very Good"
      ),
    Response_log2 = log2(1+Response),
    Cost = recode(
      cut(CPM, breaks = c(0,5,10,Inf)), 
      `(0,5]` = "Low", `(5,10]` = "Middle", `(10,Inf]` = "High"
      ),
    CPM_log2 = log2(1+CPM),
    Rate_log2 = log2(1+Rate),
    Imps_log2 = log2(1+`Imps (000)`)
    )

# calculate percentage missing by variable
missing <- df %>% 
  summarise_all(funs(sum(is.na(.)/n()))) %>% 
  gather(key="Variable", value="Pct_Missing")
# create bar chart of percent missing
missing %>% ggplot(aes(x=reorder(Variable,Pct_Missing),y=Pct_Missing))+ 
  ggtitle("Percent Missing")+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  xlab("Variable")+
  coord_flip()+
  theme_classic()

# program and property look useful but will require some cleaning
df <- df %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(Program, Property), str_to_lower) %>%
  mutate_at(vars(Program, Property), function(x) str_replace_all(string = x, pattern = "\\*|\\(|\\)", replacement = "")) %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(Program, Property), str_trim)
df %>% 
  group_by(Program, Property) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))
# just keep non-zero for Response and Cost - model them later if necessary
tmp <- df %>% filter(CPM == 0 | Response == 0)
df <- df %>% filter(CPM > 0 & Response > 0)
# Select variables to keep in final dataset
df <- df %>% 
  select(
    -Start, # Documentation says to ignore
    -End,  # Documentation says to ignore
    -`Week of`, # Redundant - same info as Date
    -`C/B/S`) # Too little variation
# Note the skewness in response
# df %$% boxplot(Response)
# Note the outlier in cost
# df %$% boxplot(CPM)
(outlier <- df %>% filter(CPM>100))
df <- df %>% filter(CPM<=100)

Finalize

Prepare the final dataset for modeling

  • Drop columns tha are not relevant for modeling
  • Examine pairwise correlations of continuous variables
dfnl <- df %>% 
  select(
    -Date, 
    -Time,
    -Program,
    -Property,
    -Rate,
    -Rate_log2,
    -`Imps (000)`,
    -Imps_log2) %>% 
  rename(
    Type = `Buy Type`, 
    Title = `Creative Title`) %>% 
  mutate(
    Network = fct_lump(Network, p = .01),
    Daypart = fct_lump(Daypart, p = .01),
    Title = fct_lump(Title, p = .01),
    Year = as.factor(Year),
    DayofWk = as.factor(DayofWk),
    Month = as.factor(Month),
    Day = as.factor(Day),
    Hour = as.factor(Hour),
    Minute = as.factor(Minute))
cor <- dfnl %>% 
  mutate_if(is.factor, as.numeric) %>%
  select(-c(Rating, Cost, Response_log2, CPM_log2)) %>% 
  cor(use = "na.or.complete") %>% 
  round(2)
# plot correlations
corrplot(cor, type = "lower") # order = "hclust", col = c("black", "white"), bg = "lightblue")

# Export the final data as CSV 
write_csv(dfnl, "final_data.csv", na = "")

# load data
dfh2o <- h2o.importFile("final_data.csv")
# partition
parts <- h2o.splitFrame(dfh2o,ratios = c(.7,.2))
train <- parts[[1]]
valid <- parts[[2]]
test  <- parts[[3]]
# Set predictor and response variables
myY <- "Response_log2"
myX <- c("Network","Daypart","Type","Length","Title","Year","Month","Day","DayofWk","Hour","Minute","CPM_log2")
# write custom functions
plot_scoring <- function(model) {
  sh <- h2o.scoreHistory(object = model)
  par(mfrow=c(1,2))
  if(model@algorithm == "gbm" | model@algorithm == "drf"){
    min <- min(range(sh$training_rmse), range(sh$validation_rmse))
    max <- max(range(sh$training_rmse), range(sh$validation_rmse))
    plot(x = sh$number_of_trees, y = sh$validation_rmse, col = "orange", main = model@model_id, ylim = c(min,max))
    points(x = sh$number_of_trees, y = sh$training_rmse, col = "blue")
    min <- min(range(sh$training_auc), range(sh$validation_auc))
    max <- max(range(sh$training_auc), range(sh$validation_auc))
    plot(x = sh$number_of_trees, y = sh$validation_auc, col = "orange", main = model@model_id, ylim = c(min,max))
    points(x = sh$number_of_trees, y = sh$training_auc, col = "blue")
    return(data.frame(number_of_trees = sh$number_of_trees, validation_auc = sh$validation_auc, validation_rmse = sh$validation_rmse))
  }
  if(model@algorithm == "deeplearning"){
    plot(x = sh$epochs, y = sh$validation_rmse, col = "orange", main = model@model_id)
    plot(x = sh$epochs, y = sh$validation_auc, col = "orange", main = model@model_id)
  }
}
